         <abstract>
            <p>A new system of fixed exchange rates is necessarily subject to the same kind of tensions that finally brought the old system into disarray. How long can a new system, obtained at the price of lengthy negotiations, summit meetings and congressional action on the dollar price of gold, be expected to last? The author explores the causes of these tensions, and suggests some compromises that might help make a new system viable.</p>
          </abstract>
